              <h3>Step 1 – Calculate the volume of stone</h3>
              <p>
                The first step is to find the volume of stone required. The
                calculator uses standard geometry formulas:
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Rectangle:</strong></p>
                <p>\( V = L \times W \times D \)</p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( L \) = length</li>
                  <li>\( W \) = width</li>
                  <li>\( D \) = depth (thickness of stone layer)</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Circle:</strong></p>
                <p>\( V = \pi \times (d/2)^2 \times D \)</p>
                <p>where \( d \) is the diameter.</p>
                <p><strong>Border / Path (approximate rectangle):</strong></p>
                <p>\( V = L \times W \times D \)</p>
              </div>

              <p>
                Internally, the calculator converts all dimensions to
                <strong>feet</strong> and depth to <strong>feet</strong> so that
                the volume is computed in cubic feet:
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Unit conversions:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>inches → feet: \( \text{ft} = \text{in} / 12 \)</li>
                  <li>
                    centimeters → meters: \( \text{m} = \text{cm} / 100 \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    meters → feet: \( \text{ft} = \text{m} \times 3.28084 \)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 2 – Convert volume to cubic yards and cubic meters</h3>
              <p>
                Once the volume in cubic feet is known, it is converted to other
                units:
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \( \text{cubic yards} = \dfrac{\text{ft}^3}{27} \) (since 1
                    yd³ = 27 ft³)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \( \text{cubic meters} = \text{ft}^3 \times 0.0283168 \)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 3 – Convert volume to weight using density</h3>
              <p>
                Stone weight depends on its density. The calculator lets you
                choose a preset or enter a custom density. The core relationship
                is:
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Weight from density:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( W_{\text{lb}} = V_{\text{ft}^3} \times
                  \rho_{\text{lb/ft}^3} \)
                </p>
                <p>Then:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( \text{tons (US)} = W_{\text{lb}} / 2000 \)</li>
                  <li>\( \text{kg} = W_{\text{lb}} \times 0.45359237 \)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <p>Density conversions used by the calculator:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \( \rho_{\text{kg/m}^3} = \rho_{\text{lb/ft}^3} \times
                    16.0185 \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \( \rho_{\text{tons/yd}^3} = \dfrac{\rho_{\text{lb/ft}^3}
                    \times 27}{2000} \)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 4 – Waste factor and coverage</h3>
              <p>
                Real projects rarely match the ideal math. To account for
                <strong>compaction, uneven ground, and cutting</strong>,
                contractors often add 5–10% extra material.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Adjusted quantity with waste:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( Q_{\text{adj}} = Q_{\text{base}} \times \left(1 +
                  \dfrac{p}{100}\right) \)
                </p>
                <p>where \( p \) is the waste percentage.</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Approximate coverage is calculated by dividing volume by depth.
                For example, for a rectangular area:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( \text{Area} = \dfrac{V}{D} \)</p>
                <p>
                  with \( V \) in ft³ and \( D \) in ft, giving area in ft².
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Typical stone densities</h2>
              <p>
                Here are common bulk densities you can use as a starting point:
              </p>
              <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left">Material</th>
                    <th class="px-3 py-2 text-right">lb/ft³</th>
                    <th class="px-3 py-2 text-right">kg/m³</th>
                    <th class="px-3 py-2 text-right">tons/yd³ (approx.)</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr class="border-t">
                    <td class="px-3 py-2">Crushed stone / gravel</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 text-right">95</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 text-right">1,520</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 text-right">1.28</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr class="border-t">
                    <td class="px-3 py-2">Pea gravel</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 text-right">90</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 text-right">1,440</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 text-right">1.22</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr class="border-t">
                    <td class="px-3 py-2">River rock</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 text-right">100</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 text-right">1,600</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 text-right">1.35</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr class="border-t">
                    <td class="px-3 py-2">Lava rock</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 text-right">55</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 text-right">880</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 text-right">0.74</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2">
                Values are approximate and can vary by quarry, stone size, and
                moisture content. Use your supplier’s density if available.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for ordering stone</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Round up, don’t down.</strong> It is usually cheaper
                  to have a little extra than to pay for a second delivery.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use deeper layers for driveways.</strong> 4–6 inches
                  (10–15 cm) is common for vehicle traffic, often in multiple
                  layers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check truck capacity.</strong> Many dump trucks carry
                  10–15 tons; compare your result to avoid overloading.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ask about moisture.</strong> Wet stone can weigh more
                  than dry stone, affecting tonnage.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How do I calculate how much stone I need?</h3>
              <p>
                Measure the length and width of the area, choose a depth, and
                multiply them to get volume. Convert the volume to cubic yards
                or cubic meters, then multiply by the stone density to get tons
                or kilograms. This calculator automates all of those steps and
                supports multiple shapes.
              </p>

              <h3>What depth of stone should I use?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Decorative stone and river rock:
                  <strong>2–3 in</strong> (5–7.5 cm)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Garden paths and walkways: <strong>3–4 in</strong> (7.5–10 cm)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Driveways and parking areas: <strong>4–6 in</strong> (10–15
                  cm), often in two layers (base + top)
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>How many tons are in a cubic yard of stone?</h3>
              <p>
                Most crushed stone and gravel weigh between
                <strong>1.3 and 1.7 tons per cubic yard</strong>. A common rule
                of thumb is about <strong>1.5 tons per cubic yard</strong>. The
                exact value depends on stone type and moisture, so adjust the
                density in the calculator if your supplier provides a specific
                number.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can I use this calculator for gravel, river rock, and decorative
                rock?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. The tool is designed for any loose aggregate: crushed
                stone, pea gravel, river rock, lava rock, and similar materials.
                Just pick the closest preset or enter a custom density.
              </p>

              <h3>Does compaction affect how much stone I need?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. When stone is spread and compacted, the layer becomes
                denser and slightly thinner. That’s why contractors usually add
                <strong>5–10% extra</strong>. Use the waste factor field to see
                both base and adjusted quantities.
              </p>
